The saturation magnetization and coercivity of the MWCNTs/Co0.85Se nanocomposites increased due to a decrease in the Co0.85Se nanoparticle size in the MWCNTs/Co0.85Se nanocomposites and an increase in the distance between the Co0.85Se nanoparticles, which increased the specific surface area, thereby benefiting the electrocatalytic performance of the catalyst. Moreover, the MWCNTs/Co0.85Se nanocomposites exhibited an excellent hydrogen evolution reaction performance owing to the presence of MWCNTs, which enhanced the mass transport during the electrocatalytic reactions. Graphical Abstract Co0.85Se magnetic nanoparticles supported on carbon nanotube enhanced the performance of electrocatalytic hydrogen production, which possesses excellent activity than that of pure Co0.85Se nanoparticle. Keywords Co0.85Se Nanocomposites Magnetic Electrocatalysis Hydrogen evolution reaction 1 Introduction As an eco-friendly and renewable clean energy, hydrogen (H2) is considered a promising alternative to fossil fuels [ 1,2 ]. A large-scale, high-efficiency, and low-cost H2 production technology is expected to be the cornerstone for developing H2 energy [ 3 ]. Undoubtedly, electrochemical water splitting via the hydrogen evolution reaction (HER) is a favorable method for the generation of H2. However, the commercialization of electrocatalytic H2 evolution is limited by the slow dynamic processes, low catalytic performance, and poor stability of the catalysts [ 1 ]. Thus, to make the entire process more energy efficient, efficient HER electrocatalysts that deliver a high current at a low overpotential (η) have attracted extensive attention [ 4 ]. At present, materials based on noble metals such as Pt, Ir, Rh, and Ru are developed because of their superior catalytic activity [ 5,6 ]. However, unfortunately, the high cost and rareness of noble metals restrict their application in the HER at a large scale. Therefore, it is important to find inexpensive, earth-abundant elements to prepare high-performance and durable electrocatalysts. In recent years, low-cost earth-abundant transition metal compounds have been developed as possible alternatives, such as NiS2/MoS2 [ 7–9 ], CoP@ZnFeP [ 10 ], CoNi2S4 [ 11 ], and Co x Ni1-x O [ 12 ]. Non-stoichiometric-phase cobalt selenide (Co0.85Se), an important metal chalcogenide, has received extensive attention owing to its excellent performance in a variety of applications such as in the fields of dye-sensitized solar cells [ 13 ], potassium-ion batteries [ 14 ], water splitting [ 1,15,16 ], and CO2 photo-reduction [ 17 ]. Interestingly, Co0.85Se and its ternary compounds, having a weak ferromagnetic property, are usually used for wastewater treatment [ 18,19 ]. Cobalt selenide is one of the promising HER electrocatalysts due to t6 2g e1 g separated from Co 3d electrons has a near-optimum electronic eg filling [ 20 ]. Liu [ 21 ] et al. reported that an amorphous CoSe film electrodeposited on a Ti mesh needs an overpotential of 121 mV to drive the HER and exhibits a small Tafel slope (84 mV dec−1). However, low-dimensional cobalt selenides have fewer active sites, poor dispersibility, and a low electron transmission capacity, which result in a poor electrocatalyst activity [ 11 ]. Therefore, to ensure more active sites to improve the charge and mass transfers for reaction, carbon materials (e.g., carbon nanotubes (CNTs), carbon cloth (CC), carbon nanofibers (CNFs), carbon fiber papers (CFPs), reduced graphene oxide (rGO), and graphdiyne) are used as high-conductivity materials to enhance the HER performance [ 22–24 ]. Multi-walled carbon nanotubes (MWCNTs) display various electronic properties such as metallic conductivity (possible electronic structure) and electron-storage capacity (one electron for every 32 carbon atoms) [ 25 ]. Hence, the specific structure of MWCNTs can effectively promote electron transfer from the electrocatalysts to the CNTs. Moreover, graphene is a zero-bandgap semiconductor in which the filled valence band and the empty conduction band are in contact with each other, thus giving rise to peculiar properties [ 26 ]. In this work, magnetic Co0.85Se nanoparticles were synthesized by a one-step hydrothermal method without using any surfactant or structure-directing agent. MWCNTs were introduced into the Co0.85Se electrocatalyst system to enhance the HER performance because of its high conductivity. The experimental results showed that the 30 wt% MWCNTs/Co0.85Se nanocomposite displayed the lowest onset overpotential (266 mV vs. RHE at 10 mA cm−2) and the smallest Tafel slope (60.5 mV dec−1) among all the electrocatalysts. Moreover, MWCNTs/Co0.85Se exhibited excellent catalytic activity and retained its durability even after 1,500 cycles at a scan rate of 10 mV s−1. This study provides a promising cost-effective hybrid electrocatalyst for HER. 2 Experimental 2.1 Materials and methods Cobalt chloride (CoCl2·6H2O, AR), Se powder (Se, AR, Macklin), ammonium fluoride (NH4F, AR), hydrazine hydrate (N2H4·H2O, AR), and commercial 20 wt% Pt/C powder (AR) were purchased from Macklin (Shanghai, China). Graphene oxide (GO) and Nafion solution (5%) were purchased from Aladdin (Shanghai, China). MWCNTs with diameters ranging from 60 to 100 nm and lengths larger than 5 μm were purchased from Shenzhen Nanotech Port Co., Ltd. 2.2 Preparation of surface partially oxidized MWCNTs and GO dispersion solution Before the partial surface oxidation, the nanotubes were immersed in 20% dilute nitric acid for 24 h to remove impurities. Then, they were washed to neutral, centrifuged, and dried at 60 °C for 12 h. Finally, surface partially oxidized MWCNTs were prepared by adding 1 g of MWCNTs, 70 mL of 98% H2SO4, and 30 mL of 30% H2O2 into a 150 mL round-bottom flask and gently stirring the mixture at 50 °C for 12 h. After the mixture was cooled to room temperature, the product was taken out and washed with deionized water thoroughly until the pH reached 7. The as-prepared MWCNTs were then collected by filtration and washed thoroughly with water and ethanol. The MWCNTs were dried at 60 °C under vacuum overnight. Further, GO was prepared by a modified Hummers’ method [ 27 ]. The GO powder was dispersed in water with a concentration of 1.0 mg mL−1 and the GO solution was sonicated for several days. Finally, the dark brown solution was centrifuged at 7000 rpm for 4 min and the supernatant was obtained for further use [ 28 ]. 2.2.1 Synthesis of Co0.85Se and MWCNTs/Co0.85Se nanocomposites MWCNTs/Co0.85Se nanocomposites were synthesized by a facile one-pot solvothermal method. First, 0.4 mmol of CoCl2·6H2O was dispersed in 84 mL of a mixed solvent composed of distilled water (72 mL) and N2H4·H2O (12 mL). Then, 0.48 mmol of Se powder, 2 mmol of NH4F, and 11.4 mg of oxidized MWCNTs were added sequentially. The solution was stirred for 20 min and then transferred to a 100 mL Teflon-lined stainless steel autoclave. The autoclave was sealed and maintained at 180 °C for 24 h in an electric oven. After the autoclave was allowed to naturally cool to room temperature, the product was collected by centrifugation, washed with water and ethanol several times, and dried at 60 °C for 12 h in a vacuum oven to obtain the nominal 30 wt% MWCNTs/Co0.85Se nanocomposite. Products with different MWCNTs-to-Co0.85Se weight ratios were fabricated by the same method. Co0.85Se nanoparticles were prepared by the same procedure in the absence of MWCNTs. 2.2.2 Synthesis of rGO/Co0.85Se nanocomposites Nominal 15 wt% rGO/Co0.85Se nanocomposites were prepared by adding 5.8 mL of the GO dispersion solution into a solution of the prepared Co0.85Se nanoparticles under the same synthesis conditions as mentioned above. The nominal rGO-to-Co0.85Se weight ratios were adjusted to 10, 15, and 20 wt%, and the obtained samples fabricated by the same method are denoted as 10 wt% rGO/Co0.85Se, 15 wt% rGO/Co0.85Se, and 20 wt% rGO/Co0.85Se, respectively. 2.3 Characterization X-ray diffraction (XRD) patterns were recorded using a Bruker D8 Advance diffractometer with a Cu radiation source (λ = 0.1540 nm). The Raman spectra were recorded under ambient conditions using a HORIBA JY LabRAM HR spectrometer. Scanning electron microscopy (SEM) and transmission electron microscopy (TEM) images were obtained on a JEOL JSM-7610 Plus instrument and a FEI F20 instrument, respectively. The chemical composition was investigated by X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS) using a Thermo Fisher EscaLab 250 Xi system. Magnetic hysteresis loops were recorded using a Quantum Design SQUID VSM at 300K. Fig. 1 Schematic illustration of the preparation of MWCNTs/Co0.85Se nanocomposite. 2.4 Measurement of electrocatalytic properties All electrocatalytic measurements were conducted on an electrochemical station (CHI660E) with a three-electrode system in a N2-saturated 0.5 M H2SO4 solution. Platinum wire and Ag/AgCl were used as the counter electrode and reference electrode, respectively. Two milligrams of Co0.85Se nanoparticles and MWCNTs/Co0.85Se and rGO/Co0.85Se nanocomposites were respectively dispersed into 1 mL of ethanol solution and sonicated for 40 min. Then, 10 µL of Nafion solution was added into the mixture solution. Thereafter, 10 µL of the above slurry was dropped on a polished glassy carbon electrode (GCE, R = 2 mm) as the working electrode and dried at room temperature before use. For comparison, commercial 20 wt% Pt/C was dispersed on a polished GCE in the same way. Linear sweep voltammetry (LSV) was performed at a scan rate of 5 mV s−1 at room temperature and the electrodes were cycled for at least 20 cycles before taking any measurement to ensure the authenticity of data. Electrochemical impedance spectroscopy (EIS) was performed at −0.2 V vs. RHE in the frequency range of 0.05 to 106 Hz with an AC voltage of 5 mV. To determine the stability of the electrocatalysts, were performed by LSV curves initially and after 1500 cycles at a scan rate of 10 mV s−1 in 0.5 M H2SO4. Moreover, the effective active surface areas (ECSAs) of the samples were studied by cyclic voltammetry (CV) performed at various scan rates from 20 to 200 mV s−1 in the potential range of 0.1 to 0.3 V (vs. RHE). 3 Results and discussion CoCl2·6H2O as a cobalt ion source, Se powder as a Se source, NH4F as a mineralizer, and N2H4·H2O as a reductant were used to synthesize Co0.85Se nanoparticles. The process of synthesis can be expressed as the following equations [ 29 ]. N2H4·H2O incomplete decomposition: (1) 3H 2 NNH 2 (l) → ⨿4(1 − x)NH 3 (g)⨿+⨿(2x+1)N 2 (g)⨿+⨿(6x)H 2 (g) N2H4·H2O complete decomposition: (2) H 2 NNH 2 (l)⨿ → N 2 (g)⨿+⨿2H 2 (g) (3) Co 2+ ⨿+⨿H 2 → 2H + ⨿+⨿Co (4) 0 .85⨿Co⨿+⨿Se → 180 ° C Co 0 .85 Se First, cobalt ions reduce into elemental cobalt by the H2 released from the decomposition of N2H4·H2O. Then, elemental cobalt reacts with Se powder to form Co0.85Se nanoparticles. The XRD patterns of the samples are displayed in Fig. 2(a) . The diffraction peaks at 33.3°, 44.7°, 50.5°, 60.3°, 61.8°, 69.9°, and 71.3° can be indexed to the (101), (102), (110), (103), (112), (202), and (004) crystal planes of hexagonal Co0.85Se (PDF# 52-1008). However, the typical peaks around 26° corresponding to MWCNTs mostly disappear, which is attributed to the dilution of Co0.85Se nanoparticles. Surprisingly, the XRD peaks of 30 wt% MWCNTs/Co0.85Se are sharper than those of Co0.85Se, which indicates the higher crystallinity of MWCNTs/Co0.85Se. A possible explanation is that the MWCNTs are beneficial for the oriented growth of Co0.85Se [ 30 ]. The interaction between Co0.85Se and MWCNTs was further characterized by Raman spectroscopy; the Raman spectra are shown in Fig. 2(b). The peaks at 184 and 675 cm−1 are attributed to the Ag and A1g modes of CoSe2, and the peaks at 466 and 520 cm−1 are assigned to the Eg and F1 2g modes of trivalent cobalt compounds, respectively [ 31 ]. In addition, the Raman spectra of MWCNTs and MWCNTs/Co0.85Se show the characteristic peaks of Co0.85Se as well as the disordered (D) and graphitic (G) peaks of MWCNTs at 1348 and 1583 cm−1, respectively, which indicate the incorporation of Co0.85Se in the MWCNTs. The D band originates from the vibration of sp 3-hybridized carbon atoms in the disordered and defective region and is proportional to the number of defects and other carbon impurities in the MWCNTs samples. On the other hand, the G band is ascribed to the E2g vibration mode of sp 2 carbon atoms [ 32 ]. The intensity ratios (I D/I G) are 1.23 and 1.02 for the MWCNTs and 30 wt% MWCNTs/Co0.85Se, respectively (Fig. 2(b)). The I D/I G ratio exhibits the graphitization of carbon-based materials as well as the defect density. The defects on the surface of the MWCNTs, as suggested by a high ID/IG ratio, allowed the deposition of Co0.85Se nanoparticles [ 25 ]. Furthermore, the peak at 2681 cm-1 corresponds to the 2D band of the graphitic lattice vibration modes due to the created defects of MWCNTs. XPS was performed to further analyze the surface chemical bonding states of 30 wt% MWCNTs/Co0.85Se; the XPS profiles are shown in Fig. 3(a)–(c) . As shown in Fig. 3(a), the 2p 3/2 peak deconvoluted into Co3+ 2p 3/2, Co2+ 2p 3/2, and shakeup satellite peaks. The peaks at 785.9 and 802.8 eV are ascribed to the shakeup satellite peaks, respectively, which is consistent with the findings of a previous report [ 15 ]. The peaks with binding energies of 781.4 and 797.5 eV correspond to Co2+ and that at 778.2 eV corresponds to Co3+ [ 33 ]. The results indicate that cobalt is present on the surface as Co2+. Figure 3(b) and Figure 3(a) display the Se 3d and Co 3p spectra. The peaks at 54.2 and 55.4 eV are assigned to Se 3d 5/2 and Se 3d 3/2, respectively, and the additional peak at around 60 eV deconvoluted into peaks corresponding to Se–O bonding structures and Co 3p [ 34,35 ]. The presence of SeO x in the samples could be ascribed to surface oxidation, which is in good agreement with previous reports [ 36 ]. The high-resolution C 1s peak of MWCNTMWCNTs/Co0.85Se (Fig. 3(c)) deconvoluted into three peaks located at 284.8, 286.2, and 288.9 eV, which are assigned to the C-C, C-O, and C=O groups, respectively [ 37,38 ]. The survey spectra of MWCNTs/Co0.85Se, rGO/Co0.85Se, and Co0.85Se as well as Co 2p, Se 3d, and C 1s spectra are shown in Fig. S2(a)–(d). SEM was performed to study the micromorphological features of the as-prepared samples (Fig. 4 ). Co0.85Se nanoparticles display irregularly shaped particles with a size of approximately 50–100 nm with some degree of agglomeration, and a relatively rough surface (Fig. 4(a) and Fig. S4); thus, the structure of Co0.85Se could provide abundant active sites. As shown in Fig. 4(b), the Co0.85Se nanoparticles are well distributed on the surface of MWCNTMWCNTs, which are uniform with a diameter of approximately 50–60 nm and length in the micrometer scale. The Co0.85Se magnetic nanoparticles were in intimate contact with the highly conductive MWCNTs support. A close contact between Co0.85Se and MWCNTs is essential for an efficient electron transport toward the active sites of Co0.85Se to MWCNTs. When GO was introduced in the reaction system, it converted into rGO nanoparticles during the hydrothermal reaction, which is confirmed by Raman analysis (Fig. S1). As shown in Fig. 4(b) and Fig. S3(a), the reduction in the size of Co0.85Se is attributed to the space confinement effect of the nanotubes and rGO layers, which provide a space-confined environment, impeding the growth of Co0.85Se nanoparticles [ 28,39 ]. The microstructures of the samples were analyzed by TEM and high-resolution TEM (HRTEM). The results shown in Fig. 5(a) corroborate that the Co0.85Se nanoparticles have an irregular morphology, and the d-spacing value of 0.202 nm corresponds to the (102) plane (Fig. 5(b)). Moreover, Fig. 5(c) shows that Co0.85Se nanoparticles with a size of ∼50 nm are grown on the surface of MWCNTs. As can be seen in Fig. 5(c), the Co0.85Se nanoparticles on the MWCNTs surface are smaller than the bare Co0.85Se, which is ascribed to the presence of MWCNTs. The crystallite structure of Co0.85Se in the nanocomposites showed no significant change. The interplanar distances of 0.27 and 0.18 nm correspond to the typical (101) and (110) planes of hexagonal Co0.85Se, respectively (Fig. 5(d)). Furthermore, it is interesting that the entire observed area of the rGO/Co0.85Se nanocomposite displays a typical monolayer rGO film and irregular nanoparticles (Fig. S3(b)). The formation of rich atomic interfaces between Co0.85Se and rGO are ascribed to their strong coupling can be seen from red marks (Fig. S3(c)) [ 40 ]. Besides, the interlayer distance of 0.37 nm corresponds to the (002) lattice plane of rGO and the d-spacing value of 0.27 nm corresponds to the (101) plane of Co0.85Se. Last but not the least, the scanning transmission electron microscopy (STEM) and EDX elemental mapping images confirmed the uniform dispersion of Co, Se, and C elements over the entire MWCNTs/Co0.85Se nanocomposites (Fig. 5(e)). The Co and Se element mapping patterns overlapped adequately with the C element mapping pattern, which suggests the successful formation of the hybrid catalyst. The magnetic hysteresis loops were measured to investigate the magnetic properties of Co0.85Se and MWCNTs/Co0.85Se at room temperature (25 °C); the plots are shown in Fig. 6 . The graphs show typical S-type curves, which indicate a ferromagnetic behavior. As shown in Fig. 6(a), the saturation magnetization (Ms), remanent magnetization (Mr), and coercivity (Hc) values of Co0.85Se are 0.035, 0.0032 emu g−1, and 55.09 Oe, respectively. The weak ferromagnetism can be attributed to the uncompensated spin on the surface of Co0.85Se. Hence, as shown in Fig. 6(b), the Ms (0.118 emu g−1), Mr (0.035 emu g−1), and Hc (158 Oe) of MWCNTs/Co0.85Se increased compared with those of Co0.85Se due to the decrease in Co0.85Se size in the MWCNTMWCNTs/Co0.85Se nanocomposites [ 41 ], which is consistent with the XRD and TEM results. The Hc increased from 55.09 Oe for the Co0.85Se nanoparticles to 158 Oe for the MWCNTs/Co0.85Se nanocomposites (Fig. 6(b)) due to the increase in the distance between the Co0.85Se nanoparticles, which resulted in weaker interparticle dipolar interactions [ 42,43 ]. The decrease in crystallite size and the increase in inter-nanoparticle distance enhanced the specific surface area of the MWCNTs/Co0.85Se catalyst, which is beneficial for the electrocatalytic activity for HER [ 44 ]. The electrocatalytic activities of the as-prepared samples for HER were tested in 0.5 M H2SO4 on a GCE with a mass loading of approximately 0.16 mg cm−2. In general, the commercial 20 wt% Pt/C catalyst shows the best HER property as a reference having a near zero onset potential and a large current density. The LSV curves of Co0.85Se, 30 wt% MWCNTs/Co0.85Se, and 20 wt% Pt/C are shown in Fig. 7(a) . The results indicate the poor HER performance of the Co0.85Se nanoparticles with an overpotential of 319 mV (vs. RHE) at 10 mA cm−2. In contrast, with the introduction of MWCNTs, the 30 wt% MWCNTs/Co0.85Se nanocomposite displayed better HER performance with a lower overpotential of 266 mV (vs. RHE) at 10 mA cm−2. Fig. S5 shows the LSV curves of MWCNTs and MWCNTs/Co0.85Se nanocomposites with different nominal weight percentages. When the mass ratio of MWCNTs increased from 15% to 30% in the MWCNTs/Co0.85Se nanocomposites, the onset potential decreased from 290 to 266 mV with an increase in current density from 60 to 83 mA cm−2 at −0.4 V (vs. RHE). The is possibly because the tubular structure of CNTs is conducive to the fast diffusion of electrolyte ions and the release of gaseous products of water electrolysis, which improved the electrocatalytic activity [ 45 ]. However, the electrocatalytic property decreased when the MWCNTs content was increased to 45%. This is because with an increase in the mass ratio of MWCNTs in the composite, the active sites in the MWCNTs/Co0.85Se nanocomposites decreased [ 38 ]. All these results strongly indicate that the introduction of moderate MWCNTs can enhance the Co0.85Se nanoparticle HER performance because of improved conductivity and a reduction in the aggregation of Co0.85Se nanoparticles. Moreover, with an increase in the content of rGO, the overpotential of rGO/Co0.85Se shows a similar trend as that of the MWCNTs/Co0.85Se nanocomposites. The 15 wt% rGO/Co0.85Se nanocomposite exhibited a significant HER at its lowest overpotential of 285 mV (vs. RHE) at 10 mA cm−2 (Fig. S5(b)). The Tafel slope is an inherent property of electrocatalysts, and a small Tafel slope indicates a strongly enhanced HER rate with a moderate increase in overpotential [ 46,47 ]. As shown in Fig. 7(b), the Tafel slope of 30 wt% MWCNTs/Co0.85Se is the smallest, which indicates the favorable reaction kinetics of the nanocomposite. The HER catalyst inherent activity was further evaluated by the exchange current density (j 0). The smallest Tafel slope and the largest exchange current density of 0.07 mA cm−2 of 30 wt% MWCNTs/Co0.85Se among all the as-synthesized catalysts further suggest that the HER occurred through a Volmer-Heyrovsky mechanism, in which the fast discharge of a proton is followed by the rate-limiting electrochemical recombination with an additional proton and a rate-determining step of the electrochemical desorption [ 48–50 ]. However, the MWCNTs/Co0.85Se composites displayed a relatively small Tafel slope of 60.5 mV dec−1 among the Co-based HER catalysts, which is close to those of Co2P/Co-Foil and Co3(PO4)2@N-C, but much better than that of CoP@ZnFeP nanocomposites (Table S1). To investigate the interface reactions and electrode kinetics, EIS was performed; the EIS profiles of the Co0.85Se nanoparticles and 30 wt% MWCNTs/Co0.85Se composite are shown in Fig. 8(a) . As can be seen from EIS measurements, the 30 wt% MWCNTs/Co0.85Se composite shows a lower impedance than the bare Co0.85Se samples under the same conditions, which is consistent with the results of Tafel slopes (Fig. 7(b)). This indicates the higher HER efficiency of MWCNTs/Co0.85Se, which can be attributed to the high electron-transfer ability and large surface area of MWCNTs [ 51,52 ]. Moreover, the effective ECSA, which is proportional to the amount of active sites for HER, was verified by capacitance measurements of the double layer at the solid-liquid interface [ 53 ]. To further demonstrate the superior catalytic performance of the 30 wt% MWCNTs/Co0.85Se nanocomposite compared with that of Co0.85Se, the double-layer capacitances (C DL) were determined by performing CV at various scan rates (20–200 mV s−1) in the potential range of 0.1–0.3 V (vs. RHE). As shown in Fig. 8(b) and Fig. S6(c), all the CV curves exhibit a regular rectangular shape, which is the typical characteristic of double-layer capacitors. Fig. 8(c) exhibits the plot of the difference in the current densities of anode and cathode versus the scan rates, in which slopes are considered the electrochemical double-layer capacitances. It can be clearly seen that the CDL of 30 wt% MWCNTs/Co0.85Se (0.22 mF cm−2) is higher than those of Co0.85Se and 15 wt% rGO/Co0.85Se (0.04 and 0.17 mF cm−2, respectively), which indicates the larger ECSA of 30 wt% MWCNTs/Co0.85Se, and thus, the preferable HER [ 54 ]. The stability of electrocatalysts is another essential criterion for the evaluation of the electrocatalytic HER performance. To evaluate the stability of the catalysts, the polarization curves were measured at a scan rate of 10 mV s−1 for 1500 cycles in an acid solution (Fig. 9(a) , Fig. S7(a)). The 30 wt% MWCNTs/Co0.85Se electrode exhibited better stability than Co0.85Se in the acid solution because of its irregular tubular structure that can accommodate the volume expansion caused by H2 gas [ 54 ]. In addition, the time-dependent graph of current density (Fig. 9(b)) displays a slight fluctuation in the HER performance of MWCNTs/Co0.85Se. The possible reason is the partial loss of the electrocatalytically active sites of the MWCNTs/Co0.85Se nanocomposite during the violent bubble accumulation and release process (inset in Fig. 9(b)) [ 55 ]. The excellent activity of 30 wt% MWCNTs/Co0.85Se for HER can be explained by the following factors: (1) the intrinsically good HER activity of nonstoichiometric Co0.85Se because of its unique intrinsic half-metallic character due to the overlap of Co 3d and Se 4p spin-up electrons (high conductivity) [ 33 ]; (2) the Co0.85Se nanoparticles synthesized using a polar organic solvent (N2H4·H2O) may have a small crystal size, rough surface, and large specific surface area, which ensured a better reactive performance and afforded ample active sites [ 2 ]; and (3) the introduction of MWCNTs as a highly conductive material increased the conductivity of the entire electrode and facilitated charge transportation between the electrocatalyst and electrolyte [ 56 ]. 4 Conclusions In this study, we synthesized weak magnetic Co0.85Se nanoparticles. MWCNTs were introduced into the Co0.85Se catalyst system as a highly conductive material to enhance the HER performance to reduce the aggregation of Co0.85Se. The Ms values of Co0.85Se and 30 wt% MWCNTs/Co0.85Se were 0.035 and 0.118 emu g−1, respectively. The MWCNTs/Co0.85Se catalyst displayed a higher activity for H2 evolution than Co0.85Se in an acid solution, which gave rise to an overpotential of 266 mV at a current density of 10 mA cm−2 and yielded a small Tafel slope of 60.5 mV dec−1. The findings present a novel strategy for the development of highly active HER catalysts based on earth-abundant elements. Conflict of Interest The authors declare no conflict of interest. coredata.dc:description: Co0.85Se magnetic nanoparticles supported on carbon nanotubes were prepared by a one-step hydrothermal method. The saturation magnetization and coercivity of the MWCNTs/Co0.85Se nanocomposites increased due to a decrease in the Co0.85Se nanoparticle size in the MWCNTs/Co0.85Se nanocomposites and an increase in the distance between the Co0.85Se nanoparticles, which increased the specific surface area, thereby benefiting the electrocatalytic performance of the catalyst. Moreover, the MWCNTs/Co0.85Se nanocomposites exhibited an excellent hydrogen evolution reaction performance owing to the presence of MWCNTs, which enhanced the mass transport during the electrocatalytic reactions. Furthermore, in an acid solution, the 30 wt% MWCNTs/Co0.85Se composite catalyst exhibited a current density of 10 mA cm−2 at a small overpotential of 266 mV vs. RHE, a small Tafel slope of 60.5 mV dec-1, and good stability for HER.
